Hi Lance,

Thank you for your response and for arranging the payment of the =
remaining temporary accommodation amount.

I would however like to clarify a few points regarding the storage of =
contents, the condition of the property, and the veterinary expenses =
that were submitted previously.

Firstly, the property is not alarmed, it does not currently have =
electricity connected, as it was disconnected following the fire by Fire =
and Emergency during the incident. For this reason, I was somewhat =
surprised to read that it had been understood to be alarmed, and I would =
appreciate clarification as to how that conclusion was reached.

Secondly, the property remains smoke-contaminated, including areas =
upstairs, even several months after the fire.

As I am now responsible for arranging and covering the decontamination =
or disposal of the salvaged items, asking me to move those items back =
into a property that is not habitable, without electricity, not alarmed, =
and still affected by smoke and chemical contamination appears =
unreasonable and inconsistent with fair and reasonable claims handling, =
particularly as it exposes the items to further risks,  contamination =
and damage.

In addition, storing contents in a fire-affected structure that has not =
been decontaminated does not appear consistent with the purpose of the =
policy benefit covering temporary storage after an insured loss, which =
exists to protect contents while the house is being made habitable. The =
contents policy wording provides cover for the reasonable costs of =
storing contents when they need to be removed following an insured loss =
while the house is being made habitable.=20

Regarding the veterinary expenses, I submitted the reimbursement request =
for NZD 395.85 on 9 October, following a discussion with the previous =
claim manager who verbally approved the reimbursement and asked me to =
provide the invoice or bank statement/proof as proof of the expense.For =
this reason, receiving a different position more than five months after =
the request was submitted is somewhat unexpected and contradicting the =
verbal approval and previous guidance.

Given that as insurers iou are required to handle claims fairly and =
within a reasonable timeframe, I would appreciate a reconsideration of =
both matters.

I look forward to your response.

Kind regards,
Raffaella



> On 12 Mar 2026, at 1:22=E2=80=AFPM, Lance O'Riley =
<Lance.ORiley@tower.co.nz> wrote:
>=20
> Good Afternoon Raffaella,
> =20
> I have requested payment is made to you today for the Temporary =
Accommodation.
> =20
> For the Vet Fees, these are not covered by your policy as your cat was =
not injured as a result of an accident with a motor vehicle as required =
by the policy.
> =20
> Veterinary fees for your domestic pet
> We=E2=80=99ll pay for veterinary fees if your domestic pet is injured =
in an accident with a motor vehicle.
> Any claim under this benefit will be excess-free.
> We pay this benefit in addition to your contents sum insured.
> =20
> Limit
> We=E2=80=99ll pay up to $500 for each event
> =20
> I have discussed the storage of contents items with our assessing team =
and have had confirmation that these currently able to be stored safely =
and securely in the property which we understand is also alarmed.  For =
this reason, we would not currently cover storage costs for you, as =
there is no need for items to be stored in a commercial storage =
facility.  However, this is likely to change when the repairs actually =
start, at this time we can review any change in circumstances and =
reimburse the reasonable costs for items to be stored in a commercial =
storage facility.  Please note that any reimbursement of costs will =
still need to go through our normal approval process.=20
> =20
> Hopefully this covers off your questions, however I am more than happy =
to provide additional clarity if required.
> =20
> Kind Regards=20
